stylometry: Safety-stock is the stock that inventory managers want to keep on hand between deliveries of their next order of inventory.  The variables that need to be considered are the amount of days between the order being placed and when it is delivered (lead time) because they need enough inventory on hand to satisfy the demand for their consumers.  After determining the lead time, they should look at the average amount of sales per day or the average amount of customers per day and adjust the safety stock accordingly.  They also need to consider unforeseen circumstances such as damage to inventory, production machines malfunctioning, etc. that may cause the delay of the inventory making it to the store on time.  It can sometimes be tricky to determine safety stock because you want to have enough inventory on hand to satisfy your demand, but you don't want to have too much because then you may risk paying extra holding costs.
